{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17609145","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17609145"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:41:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:41:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16090"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16090","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16090"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.18,0.05,0,0.77]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8781"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72917"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8781","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8781"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16090"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58387"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1217"},{"type":"tags","id":"4379"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20968"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20972"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72917","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72917"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA pregnant woman has been diagnosed with a bi-lobed placenta and velamentous cord insertion. Ultrasound imaging shows unprotected fetal blood vessels running through the foetal membranes across the cervix.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Complete placental abruption","Placenta previa","Placenta accreta","Partial placental abruption","Vasa previa"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVasa previa\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when fetal blood vessels, unsupported by the umbilical cord or placental tissue, traverse the foetal membranes over the internal cervical os. This condition is strongly associated with velamentous cord insertion and bi-lobed (succenturiate) placentas. If these vessels tear during labour, rapid fetal exsanguination can occur.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplete placental abruption\u003C/strong\u003E involves total separation of the placenta from the uterine wall, not abnormal vessel placement\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlacenta previa\u003C/strong\u003E involves the placenta approaching or covering the cervical os\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlacenta accreta\u003C/strong\u003E involves abnormal placental invasion into the myometrium\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPartial placental abruption\u003C/strong\u003E involves partial separation of the placenta, not abnormal vessel placement\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEarly diagnosis of vasa previa is crucial as planned caesarean delivery before membrane rupture can prevent catastrophic foetal hemorrhage.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Vasa previa occurs when foetal blood vessels run through the membranes across the internal cervical os, unprotected by placental tissue or umbilical cord.","Vasa previa is associated with velamentous cord insertion and bilobed (succenturiate) placentas.","Rupture of vasa previa during labour can cause rapid fetal exsanguination and death."],"references":["Oyelese Y, Javinani A, Shamshirsaz AA. Vasa Previa. Obstet Gynecol. 2023 Sep 1;142(3):503-518. doi: 10.1097/AOG.0000000000005287. Epub 2023 Aug 3. PMID: 37590981; PMCID: PMC10424826.","Oyelese Y, Javinani A, Shamshirsaz AA. Vasa Previa. Obstet Gynecol. 2023 Sep 1;142(3):503-518. doi: 10.1097/AOG.0000000000005287. Epub 2023 Aug 3. PMID: 37590981; PMCID: PMC10424826.","Pavalagantharajah S, Villani LA, D\u0027Souza R. Vasa previa and associated risk factors: a systematic review and meta-analysis. Am J Obstet Gynecol MFM. 2020 Aug;2(3):100117. doi: 10.1016/j.ajogmf.2020.100117. Epub 2020 Apr 15. PMID: 33345868.","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press.","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58387"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16090"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58387","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58387"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-22T17:02:18+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-22T17:02:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8781"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72917"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":nul